</p>
<p class="side-note" style="border-left: 5px solid #FF4500">"Spare the rod, spoil the universe."--Daniel Kraken</p>
<p>
They had no idea what it’s like. To be thought of as a slimy, scrub race of ugly squid. To scrape your way to the top of your academy’s class, to chafe under the myopic yoke of nasty, backbiting bureaucrats who refused to grant him captaincy. And then to finally be granted that captaincy, but to be tasked with shipping wine (which is putrid, mewling compromise between crisp beer and delicious liquor) to every backwater planet in this arm of the galaxy.
</p>
<p>
“I am an emperor,” sniffed Daniel, giving the globe in his study a desultory spin. “And this is only one world of many that I will control utterly. And right now it’s refusing to cooperate. At this rate, they'll never know true progress. They'll never get to run their hands over the dewy hood of a black Ford 250 Super Duty in the morning before going to work.”
</p>
<p>
Yes, the Butterfly Boar was scary. It was a beast that was so far unstoppable. It was trampling his vertically integrated dreams to to powder. Daniel almost wished he were back in the simpler, wilder times when it was just he and Merlot Bot, taming the island over centuries. In their first month on land they had made tremendous progress in scouring the island of its giants. He had quenched each metal part of their matching flintlocks in red wine from good old MB himself. They had hunted together, feasting on the powder keg sized thighs of the greasy, iridescently green feathered pheasant with razor sharp bills and three foot long claws. They had tricked the last Night Pharaoh into his tomb, slowly closing him in an obsidian shell that clicked like a powder compact over the twinkling purple salt that Daniel had promised would grant him immortality. They had held dry kernels of the first crop of corn in their fists, and watched the deer come out of the jungle to nibble and sometimes, to Daniel’s surprise, to speak.

</p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
After centuries together Daniel did try to reach out to Merlot Bot. He talked about how when they finally made it to circuitry, maybe he could restore some rudimentary personality traits to the idle automatons. He had let Merlot Bot grow grapes! Had even made champagne for a couple years!
</p>
<p>
All for naught.
</p>
<p>
“Oh well,” thought Daniel. “Just a sign I’m growing soft.” It was time to put his money where his mouth would have been had it not been a cleverly molded prosthesis designed to hide his scalloped, reaching beak. He went over to his desk and pulled out a drawer with a false bottom. He slid the false bottom’s cover forward to reveal this world’s first telegraph key, his little cricket.
</p>
<p>
For its size it was incredibly heavy. He had sanded and shellacked the base himself from a slab of ironwood. John Carver had crafted the knob from the ivory of Leviathan Prime, the very first whale towed in by a galleon of gibbering asylum probationers. Its scrollwork showed a simple moon partially obscured by a thunderstorm. The metal parts were brass, of course. A brass nameplate shone across the side of the base. It said, “The Lightning Guild.”
</p>
<p>
The Bolts loved talking through the telegraph. They thought it was hilarious how a little being like Daniel, whose flesh was flammable, whose thoughts were a mushy combination of chemical and current, had to use this enormously complicated machine to tame a minuscule sliver of their essence in order to beg for them to interfere in his ragged, tawdry, mortal affairs. Daniel began to tap out his request to immolate.
</p>
<p>
“Of course, Daniel!” said the first bolt who answered. Discussion of payment would take at least a thousand generations for the lightning guild. It took thirty seconds for Daniel. They wanted solid gold pylons strung from end to end  across the island, starting from the top of Mount Oligarch, where they could reach it the most easily. They wanted gold skulls molded onto the top, their mouths open to the rain, and snowflakes, and night sky.
</p>
<p>
“Agreed,” said Daniel, bankrupting himself for the next century. He was speaking, of course, to a vastly different guild master than the one he had initially contacted. A breath for Daniel. An eon of lightning time.
</p>
<p>
“We’re sending a bolt to assist you momentarily,” advised the embattled president of a lightning society already clamoring to renegotiate with Daniel. Silver was now all the rage. “However, we do have some concerns.”
</p>
<p>
“What?” asked Daniel, his eyes widening in surprise.
</p>
<p>
“Well,” replied the matriarch of the shock commune, “we usually don’t like to strike targets that are this close to the client.”
</p>
<p>
“Oh no,” said Daniel, running over to throw open his windows and lean out across the balustrade.
</p>
